	<section>
		<title>Keyboard Entry of Unicode Characters</title>
		<para>This method also works only if your keyboard has a numeric keypad.</para>
		<para>A registry setting is required. If you do not know what the registry is, or
		don't feel comforable making registry changes, then don't use this method.</para>
		<para>Start <literal>regedit</literal> or <literal>regedt32</literal>. 
		Under <filename>HKEY_Current_User/Control Panel/Input Method</filename>,
		set EnableHexNumPad to "1". If you must add this entry, set the type to "REG_SZ".
		Restart your computer.</para>
		<para>To enter characters, press and hold the Alt key, press the "+" key on the
		numeric keypad, enter the Unicode character's hex code, then release the Alt key.
		The character is displayed after you release the Alt key. For example, the code
		"00bf" results in the character "¿". See 
		<link xlink:href='http://unicode.org/charts/'><emphasis role='underline'>Unicode
		6.2 Character Code Charts</emphasis></link> for a map of all Unicode
		characters and their codes.</para>
	</section>
	<section>
		<title>Character Map Utility</title>
		<para>Microsoft Windows comes with a utility called Character Map that allows
		the user to select characters that are not available directly from the keyboard.
		Character Map may be started from Start Menu => All Programs => Accessories => 
		System Tools => Character Map. See 
		<link xlink:href='http://symbolcodes.tlt.psu.edu/accents/charmap.html'><emphasis role='underline'>Character
		Map Utility</emphasis></link>
		for information on how to use Character Map.</para>
		<caution>
			<para>If you use Character Map to input a character that is not in the same
			font face as the text you are entering the character into, then a different or
			no character may be displayed.</para>
		</caution>
		<caution>
			<para>If you enter a special character into a text item and then change the
			font face for the text item, a different character may be displayed.</para>
		</caution>
	</section>
	<section>
		<title>AllChars</title>
		<para>AllChars is a utility that mimics the Compose key of Unix and Linux systems on
		Windows. It allows for the easy entry of accented and special characters like
		ù and £, by pressing the Compose key and then two other characters. The Compose
		key is configurable to be any of the Alt, Ctrl, Windows or Menu keys on the keyboard.
		Characters are formed by pressing and releasing the Compose key and then pressing and
		releasing the two keys that represent the character.</para>
		<para>See 
		<link xlink:href='http://sourceforge.net/projects/allchars/'><emphasis role='underline'>AllChars</emphasis></link>
		to download the program and to get more information.</para>
	</section>
